#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:1
msgid "Path clarity"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.31](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.31-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:5
msgid ""
"The module system is often one of the hardest things for people new to Rust. "
"Everyone has their own things that take time to master, of course, but "
"there's a root cause for why it's so confusing to many: while there are "
"simple and consistent rules defining the module system, their consequences "
"can feel inconsistent, counterintuitive and mysterious."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:11
msgid ""
"As such, the 2018 edition of Rust introduces a few new module system "
"features, but they end up _simplifying_ the module system, to make it more "
"clear as to what is going on."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:15
msgid "Here's a brief summary:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:17
msgid "`extern crate` is no longer needed in 99% of circumstances."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:18
msgid "The `crate` keyword refers to the current crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:19
msgid "Paths may start with a crate name, even within submodules."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:20
msgid "Paths starting with `::` must reference an external crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:21
msgid ""
"A `foo.rs` and `foo/` subdirectory may coexist; `mod.rs` is no longer needed "
"when placing submodules in a subdirectory."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:23
msgid "Paths in `use` declarations work the same as other paths."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:25
msgid ""
"These may seem like arbitrary new rules when put this way, but the mental "
"model is now significantly simplified overall. Read on for more details!"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:28
msgid "More details"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:30
msgid "Let's talk about each new feature in turn."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:32
msgid "No more `extern crate`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:34
msgid ""
"This one is quite straightforward: you no longer need to write `extern "
"crate` to import a crate into your project. Before:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:38
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:131
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:238
msgid "// Rust 2015\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:47
msgid "After:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:50
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:152
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:271
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:301
msgid "// Rust 2018\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:57
msgid ""
"Now, to add a new crate to your project, you can add it to your `Cargo."
"toml`, and then there is no step two. If you're not using Cargo, you already "
"had to pass `--extern` flags to give `rustc` the location of external "
"crates, so you'd just keep doing what you were doing there as well."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:62
msgid ""
"One small note here: `cargo fix` will not currently automate this change. We "
"may have it do this for you in the future."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:65
msgid "An exception"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:67
msgid ""
"There's one exception to this rule, and that's the \"sysroot\" crates. These "
"are the crates distributed with Rust itself. We'd eventually like to remove "
"the requirement for `extern crate` for them as well, but it hasn't shipped "
"yet."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:71
msgid "You'll need to use `extern crate` for:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:73
msgid "`proc_macro`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:75
msgid "Additionally, you would need to use it for:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:77
msgid "`core`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:78
msgid "`std`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:80
msgid ""
"However, `extern crate std;` is already implicit, and with `#![no_std]`, "
"`extern crate core;` is already implicit. You'll only need these in highly "
"specialized situations."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:84
msgid "Finally, on nightly, you'll need it for crates like:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:86
msgid "`alloc`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:87
msgid "`test`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:89
msgid "Macros"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:91
msgid ""
"One other use for `extern crate` was to import macros; that's no longer "
"needed. Check [the macro section](../macros/macro-changes.md) for more."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:94
msgid "Renaming crates"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:96
msgid "If you've been using `as` to rename your crate like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:104
msgid ""
"then removing the `extern crate` line on its own won't work. You'll need to "
"do this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:112
msgid "This change will need to happen in any module that uses `f`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:114
msgid "The `crate` keyword refers to the current crate"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:116
msgid ""
"In `use` declarations and in other code, you can refer to the root of the "
"current crate with the `crate::` prefix. For instance, `crate::foo::bar` "
"will always refer to the name `bar` inside the module `foo`, from anywhere "
"else in the same crate."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:121
msgid ""
"The prefix `::` previously referred to either the crate root or an external "
"crate; it now unambiguously refers to an external crate. For instance, `::"
"foo::bar` always refers to the name `bar` inside the external crate `foo`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:125
msgid "Extern crate paths"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:127
msgid ""
"Previously, using an external crate in a module without a `use` import "
"required a leading `::` on the path."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:136
#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:155
msgid "// this works in the crate root\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:142
msgid ""
"// but in a submodule it requires a leading :: if not imported with `use`\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:148
msgid ""
"Now, extern crate names are in scope in the entire crate, including "
"submodules."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:161
msgid "// crates may be referenced directly, even in submodules\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:167
msgid "No more `mod.rs`"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:169
msgid "In Rust 2015, if you have a submodule:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:172
msgid ""
"// This `mod` declaration looks for the `foo` module in\n"
"// `foo.rs` or `foo/mod.rs`.\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:177
msgid ""
"It can live in `foo.rs` or `foo/mod.rs`. If it has submodules of its own, it "
"_must_ be `foo/mod.rs`. So a `bar` submodule of `foo` would live at `foo/bar."
"rs`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:181
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018 the restriction that a module with submodules must be named "
"`mod.rs` is lifted. `foo.rs` can just be `foo.rs`, and the submodule is "
"still `foo/bar.rs`. This eliminates the special name, and if you have a "
"bunch of files open in your editor, you can clearly see their names, instead "
"of having a bunch of tabs named `mod.rs`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:218
msgid "`use` paths"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:220
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.32](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.32-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:222
msgid ""
"Rust 2018 simplifies and unifies path handling compared to Rust 2015. In "
"Rust 2015, paths work differently in `use` declarations than they do "
"elsewhere. In particular, paths in `use` declarations would always start "
"from the crate root, while paths in other code implicitly started from the "
"current scope. Those differences didn't have any effect in the top-level "
"module, which meant that everything would seem straightforward until working "
"on a project large enough to have submodules."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:230
msgid ""
"In Rust 2018, paths in `use` declarations and in other code work the same "
"way, both in the top-level module and in any submodule. You can use a "
"relative path from the current scope, a path starting from an external crate "
"name, or a path starting with `crate`, `super`, or `self`."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:235
msgid "Code that looked like this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:267
msgid ""
"will look exactly the same in Rust 2018, except that you can delete the "
"`extern crate` line:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:298
msgid "The same code will also work completely unmodified in a submodule:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:330
msgid ""
"This makes it easy to move code around in a project, and avoids introducing "
"additional complexity to multi-module projects."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-2018/module-system/path-clarity.md:333
msgid ""
"If a path is ambiguous, such as if you have an external crate and a local "
"module or item with the same name, you'll get an error, and you'll need to "
"either rename one of the conflicting names or explicitly disambiguate the "
"path. To explicitly disambiguate a path, use `::name` for an external crate "
"name, or `self::name` for a local module or item."
msgstr ""
